name: dodecanol
Reason: Alkanes have relatively low melting points due to their nonpolar nature and the London dispersion forces being the only type of intermolecular interactions present. Each methylene group (-CH2-) in an alkane contributes incrementally to the melting point. Methane is a gas at room temperature. As the carbon chain increases, we see an increase in the melting point. As a basic unit, ethane (-CH3CH3) is still a gas. We can estimate for linear alkanes that each additional methylene group adds roughly 2°C to the melting point. Dodecanol has 11 methylene groups more than ethane. The hydroxyl group (-OH) in dodecanol adds significantly to the melting point due to the capacity for hydrogen bonding, which is much stronger than London dispersion forces. A typical hydroxyl group in an alcohol can raise the melting point by about 50 to 100°C compared to a similar alkane. Since dodecanol is a straight chain alcohol, we'll estimate at the lower end of this range.
Prediction: Assuming ethane as a gaseous reference with effectively a melting point of below 0°C, addition of 11 methylene groups to form dodecane would give an estimated increase of 22°C (11 groups * 2°C/group). The hydroxyl group in dodecanol can be predicted to add approximately 50°C. Therefore, the predicted melting point of dodecanol would be 0 + 22 + 50 = 72°C
